Node.Notes: Uncertain. Tree assumes give ear to my prayer, [I speak] without lips of deceit.
The lack of "from" makes this difficult as it seems to be "I have kept the ways of the violent." Most argue for "kept from/avoided."
(SYNTAX) While participle may become substantive, the morph needs to be hiphil participle masculine singular absolute here since a participle is needed.
Figure for pupil of the eye.
Uncertain. Tree assumes apposition to the wicked. Alternatively, could be S-V-PP: my mortal enemies encompass me!
Many change vowels to yield "they advance upon me," instead of our steps. Tree assumes "they have surrounded us now in our steps."
""Rescue" from previous verse carried over; "rescue with your hand from men who are from this world.""

Uncertain. Depends on what "your treasure/what you have stored up " is. Some take as something like let the family of the wicked suffer to the third generation. Some take as descriptive of what men of this world do for their descendants. Tree assumes "your treasure" as collective for God's treasured one, the godly.
Could be "be satisfied with sons" or "sons will be satisfied/will eat their fill."
